1 WHEREAS, Mr. Cochran graduated from Loyola Law School on June 1, 1962, and
2 began preparation for the California Bar Exam; after learning that he passed the exam, he
3 returned to the city attorney's office as a deputy attorney; and
4 WHEREAS, Mr. Cochran began his work as an attorney on January 10, 1963, and
5 by 1965, he was regarded as one of the city attorney's top trial lawyers; he left the city
6 attorney's office in March 1965 and began a private practice with Gerald D. Lenoir; soon
7 after, he represented numerous clients who were involved in the Watts Riots and renewed
8 his commitment to effect change in the criminal and civil justice systems; and
9 WHEREAS, Mr. Cochran started his own practice with a goal to remedy the
10 disconnect between the community and local government by working within the legal
11 system; while continuing his criminal defense work, he began handling an increasing
12 number of civil cases; and
13 WHEREAS, Mr. Cochran was appointed to represented Willie Stafford, a member
14 of the Black Panther Party, following a December 1969 shootout between the party, the FBI,
15 and the LAPD's Criminal Conspiracy Division; in December 1971, he made his closing
16 arguments in defense of Stafford and the other party members on trial; he secured not guilty
17 verdicts for the majority of the seventy-two charges alleged against his clients; and
18 WHEREAS, Mr. Cochran worked tirelessly to overturn Geronimo Pratt's wrongful
19 murder conviction; Mr. Pratt was a Black Panther Party leader and decorated veteran of the
20 Vietnam War who received two Bronze Stars, a Silver Star, and two Purple Hearts for his
21 service; his conviction was vacated on June 10, 1997, after twenty-seven years; and
22 WHEREAS, Mr. Cochran was known as the go-to attorney for many celebrities in
23 the 1990s; his clients included Tupac Shakur, Snoop Dogg, Sean Combs, Michael Jackson,
24 Jim Brown, and Riddick Bowe; he is most famously remembered as one of O.J. Simpson's
25 defense attorneys during the internationally televised trial; and
26 WHEREAS, Johnnie Cochran, Jr., was a dedicated servant of the people who
27 established himself as one of the best trial attorneys in American history, and it is most
28 fitting to honor his historic legacy.
29 THEREFORE, BE IT RESOLVED that the House of Representatives of the
30 Legislature of Louisiana does hereby commemorate the legacy of Shreveport native Johnnie
